Objective:

Feature engineering

loan <- loan %>% 
  mutate(high_balance = ifelse(checking_balance != "< 0 DM" & savings_balance != "< 100 DM", 2, 1)) %>% 
  mutate()

Model Fitting

2 algorithms are used to build models for classifying the loan defaults. The dataset is split into train and test set for cross-validation purposes.

#baseline accuracy
acc_base <- round(700/1000,3)
paste("Baseline Accuracy: ", acc_base, "%")

Compare models

The 2 models were compared using confusion matrix metrics. Accuracy, Sensitivity and Specificity scores are fairly high, which means majority of loans were correctly predicted to be fully serviced. However, the Specificity score is low, which means loan defaulters are not correctly classified, and this is a problem for the bank (default risk is high).

data.frame(row.names = c("Accuracy", "Sensitivity", "Specificity", "Precision"), cbind(tree_vals,rf_vals))
##             tree_vals rf_vals

## Sensitivity     0.879   0.856
## Specificity     0.485   0.485
## Precision       0.768   0.764

LBB Task

Use any of the 3 classification algorithms you’ve learned to predict the risk status of a bank loan. The variable default in the dataset indicates whether the applicant did default on the loan issued by the bank. Start by reading the loan.csv dataset in, a dataset that is originally from Professor Dr. Hans Hofmann. (Refer to our RMD for the explanation of each predictors)

Use an R Markdown document to lay out your process, and explain the methodology in 1 or 2 brief paragraph. The student should be awarded the full (3) points when: - The preprocessing steps are done, and the student show an understanding of holding out a test / cross validation set for an estimate of the model’s performance on unseen data - The model’s performance is sufficiently explained (accuracy may not be the most helpful metric here! Recall about what you’ve learned regarding specificity and sensitivity) - The student demonstrated extra effort in evaluating his/her model, and proposes ways to improve the accuracy obtained from the initial model

Summary

The random forest model is not much better than an initial decision tree model. The metric scores were similar. Even though there was an attempt to feature engineer, one feature might not be enough to significantly improve the prediction capability of the model. To improve the accuracy scores obtained from initial models, better and more features should be created after more data analysis is carried out. Also, the model could be fine-tuned as well to optimize the model to given dataset, such as checking the optimum number of trees used and number of variables tried.
